Yes — your screenshot shows the root cause.

Python is importing sigmf as a namespace package:

sigmf module: <module 'sigmf' (namespace) from ['/usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages/sigmf']>
sigmf file: None
dir: []

That is why this fails:

from sigmf import SigMFFile

In the normal SigMF Python package, from sigmf import SigMFFile is supposed to work. The official docs show exactly that import pattern.  ￼

So your installed sigmf on that machine is not a healthy normal install of the expected package. It looks like a broken or conflicting install, and it is also landing under a Python 3.12 path, while your earlier UHD/GNU Radio work was using Python 3.8. That mismatch is another red flag. Your screenshot shows sigmf resolving from /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages/sigmf, while the host/container Python you were using earlier reported 3.8.x. A package installed for one interpreter is not reliably usable from another.  ￼

Best fix

On the machine where you are running waterfall_sigmf.py, clean out the broken sigmf install and reinstall it for the exact Python you are using to run the script.

Run these:

python3 -c "import sys; print(sys.executable); print(sys.version)"
python3 -m pip uninstall -y sigmf
python3 -m pip install --upgrade --no-cache-dir sigmf
python3 - <<'PY'
import sigmf
print("sigmf module:", sigmf)
print("sigmf file:", getattr(sigmf, "__file__", "no __file__"))
from sigmf import SigMFFile
print("SigMFFile import OK:", SigMFFile)
PY

If that still shows a namespace package or SigMFFile import fails, also check for conflicting installs:

python3 -m pip show sigmf
python3 - <<'PY'
import sys
print("\n".join(sys.path))
PY
find /usr/local/lib -path '*sigmf*' 2>/dev/null
find /usr/lib -path '*sigmf*' 2>/dev/null

Fast workaround

If you want to keep moving immediately, I would temporarily remove the SigMF dependency from the GUI script and just get the styled spectrogram stable first. Then add SigMF back after the Python package is clean.

One more likely cause

If you previously installed something into a different Python, it can help to be explicit:

python3.8 -m pip install --upgrade --no-cache-dir sigmf
python3.8 waterfall_sigmf.py ...

or whatever exact interpreter you are using on that box.

The key point is: the current sigmf import on that machine is wrong, and your screenshot proves it.
